Cinq vérités concernant le terrorisme
SÃO PAULO – The American policy is being held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one out of six Americans, or about 16% of the population, now placed terrorism at the top of the country's problems – an increase of 3% in a month.
Over the past ten years, never had so many Americans been this concerned about terrorism, even though their number is still far below the 46% recorded the day after the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this evolution in public opinion were especially felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
The candidacy of Donald Trump, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly inflamed (if not incendiary), has undoubtedly benefited from this.
Certain politicians feel justified in referring to the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War."
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But both presidential candidates, as well as some media outlets, who follow the old adage "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated its proportions.
To place terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – like others – keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theatre.
Terrorists are more concerned with grabbing attention and dominating the political news than with the number, per se, of their victims.
Islamic State (IS) takes great care with its staging.
The barbaric beheadings broadcast on social networks are intended to destabilize and outrage – and consequently to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating their consequences and making headlines with every terrorist act is playing into the terrorists' hands.
Terrorism is not the most serious threat facing populations in developed countries.
Terrorism kills far fewer people than car accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than to be killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be murdered by a terrorist is, according to experts, one in 3.5 million.
Americans run a greater risk of dying in their bathtub (a probability of 1 in 950,000), from an accident caused by a household appliance (a probability of 1 in 1.5 million), from a deer or elk crossing the road (a probability of 1 in 2 million), or in a passenger plane crash (a probability of 1 in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year while driving, texting or talking on their cell phones.
That is several hundred times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings in universities or schools.
Terrorism is not World War III.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to put out a terrorist surge.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, from the "autonomous" left, diverted planes across national borders and kidnapped or killed business executives or political leaders (as well as ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon dressed in a religious costume.
Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people whose identities have been destroyed by globalization, who are seeking meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of ISIS limits its appeal.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
ISIS will ultimately be defeated, just as the transnational terrorist movements that preceded it have been.
Terrorism is like jiu-jitsu.
The weaker of the two adversaries uses the strength of the stronger to defeat it.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have succeeded in overthrowing one.
But if they manage to shock and provoke citizens of a state enough to push them to futile actions, they can hope to gain the advantage.
In 2001, Al-Qaida managed to draw Americans into Afghanistan.
ISIS was born from the ruins of the US-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, it takes intelligent power (smart power).
Intelligent power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the army and police with the power of influence (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
The power of influence is also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery who the irreconcilables seek to recruit.
That is why the attention given to the narrative of events and the way the actions of the United States are commented on in social networks is as important and necessary as precision airstrikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the goodwill that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
Reason why the anti-Islam stance of some of the current candidates for the presidential election is so counterproductive.
The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It constitutes an important factor in our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of the reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap laid by the terrorists.
Let us not fill the theatre where the actions carried out by brutes and crooks take place.
If we leave them the big stage of our public speech, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and divert our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
